KISIMGIUNITCHUTIN-"You are NOT Alone!"
This week, September 7-11, 2020, is Suicide Prevention and Awareness Week.
Guidance Counselors from Tikigaq School in Point Hope, from Nunamiut School in Anaktuvuk Pass, and from Kiita Learning Community in Utqiagvik will be guests on the NSBSD radio hour at 10:00 am, Wednesday, September 9, 2020, on KBRW. If you have questions and concerns about this very important subject, please, call in during the program at 852-6811 in Barrow and for outside of Barrow call in at 1-888-852-3370.
Remember, you are NOT alone- KISIMGIUNITCHUTIN!

The NSBSD is committed to continuing to provide meals to students during this closure. In the villages the front entry of the school will be set as a distribution site. In Barrow, Ipalook and HMS will be distribution sites. You will be able to pick up meals there however no students or community members will be permitted to stay in the school. For tomorrow breakfast will be available for pickup from 8:30-9:30. Lunch will be available from 11:30-12:30. Sites will make adjustments and local announcements as necessary. Elder meals will continue to be provided for delivery. If there is any student who is physically unable to collect meals please contact your school site and we will do our best to coordinate delivery.

Thank you for your patience during this time.

post_text:
The announcement from Governor Dunleavy states that all K12 schools will be closed until March 30. All staff will still report to their duty stations on Monday, March 16 with the goal of developing further educational platforms in case of further closures. During this time, teacher inservice days will count toward student contact days. In addition, all after school activities will be cancelled during this time. This is a very fluid situation where we will be providing further guidance as we determine next steps.

The North Slope Borough School District is suspending student and staff off-slope travel. This will begin immediately and will last for the foreseeable future. While youth seem to be resilient to the COVID-19 virus, we know that youth can, and will, interact with higher risk community members. These measures are to help protect our students and communities from any spread. We currently have several staff and student groups that are off-slope this weekend. We are working to ensure their safe return as quickly as possible.

Thank you for your resilience through this process.

Our community experienced a tragic loss this week. Darren Soiyak Norton, a student at Barrow High School, has passed away. This weekend Soiyak was expected to graduate, he was about to step beyond the classroom into endless possibilities. This bright and caring young man will be missed by so many. To his family, friends, and community, the NSBSD family mourns with you.

Our team will be monitoring individual student needs related to this tragedy and we want to thank the Health Department for providing additional support to our students and staff. We ask for peace and comfort to those who are mourning, and we ask that each of us take an extra moment to check in on those around us.

Please contact the principal or school counselor if you or someone you know needs assistance during this difficult time.

post_text:
Ice Safety

Many people use the Rivers and Lakes around our communities and villages to travel on in the fall and winter. The North Slope Borough School District reminds you that, during fall freeze up, these lakes and rivers are extremely DANGEROUS.

Traveling on them by snow machine and or on foot when the ice is thin can cause you to break through. Even though the lakes and rivers are sometimes shallow, you can still get caught under the ice and drown.
PLEASE, remind students to not ride or walk on thin ice!

Lagoon Safety
We ask everyone to help with talking to children about lagoon safety. The uncertainty of the thickness of the ice along with the danger in playing near the edge are tempting to children who don’t always think ahead of what might happen if the ice breaks. Your help in reminding children about the dangers of the lagoon this time of year is greatly appreciated!

PSA from NSB Health and Special Services:
Foxes are a normal part of the ecosystem.
NOT ALL FOXES ARE RABID.
Signs of rabies include: stumbling, aggression, and biting inanimate objects.
Please call the NSB Veterinary Clinic at (907)852-0277 if you witness a fox exhibiting these abnormal behavioral signs.
The rodent (lemmings, weasels, voles) population is increased this year resulting in foxes getting closer to town.

Please vaccinate your animals for rabies every year!
Thank you!

All NSBSD students need to register to ride the bus EVERY school year. This includes all returning and new students.

Utqiaġvik Residents: Register for the School Bus in Utqiaġvik.
Transportation support staff will be at the front entry of the AC Store on Friday and Saturday, Aug 10 and 11 from 11am to 6pm to assist families with filling out and submitting registration forms for children to ride the school bus.

You can also stop by the School District Transportation Office, across from the high school, at 1683 Okpik Street to register your child(ren) for school bus services from 8:30 am – 5:00 pm. Just follow the signs to the office along the side of the building.

Non- Utqiaġvik bus registration times and registration locations are specific to each school site. Please check with your school to find out when and where to do this.

Our Transportation Manager, Chris Battle, and transportation staff are available from 8am-5pm to answer any of your questions. 907-852-8987 or 852-5311 or chris.battle@nsbsd.org

Videographers visited Fred Ipalook Elementary in April to film videos for the PLAY EVERY DAY campaign. They created several new videos that will be aired and shared online during the summer and fall. The videos feature students from NSBSD, as well as districts throughout the state.

In 2012, the Department of Health and Social Services (DHSS) launched the Play Every Day campaign to increase public awareness about the health risks of childhood obesity and the importance of physical activity and choosing healthy drinks to prevent and reduce obesity. The goal is to promote and support physically active families and children. The department is a partner of Healthy Futures, which organizes and runs the free Healthy Futures Challenge for elementary-age children.
More about Play Every Day: www.facebook.com/playeverydayak

Competitive Award Opportunities:
The Anaġi Leadership Award was created to acknowledge the leadership of Arctic Slope Regional Corporation’s former president, Jacob Anaġi Adams. This award covers tuition, fees, books, room and board, and shall be used for college or training.

The Ivalu Scholarship was created to honor eligible applicants who are making noteworthy and influential contributions to their community through their community cultural service commitment of their personal time to projects and activities which strongly incorporate the Iñupiaq values. Applicant selected should serve as a role model of implementing and following the 12 Iñupiaq Core Values while performing community cultural service activities.

SYNC makes available two FREE audiobook downloads every week, to each and every registered listener, all summer. Teens, librarians, club leaders, and educators may sign up for email or text alerts and can learn more at www.audiobooksync.com.

Any individual may participate by downloading the OverDrive Appto their device of choice and returning to the SYNC website each Thursday after 7am Eastern Time to download the new audiobook pair for the week. Each title is available for one week only, but once downloaded they can be kept forever, so the opportunity to listen can extend well beyond the term of the summer program.

Finally, they add color to their drawing.

post_text:
Read about Skiku/Nana visits to NSBSD schools in Wainwright and Anaktuvuk Pass.

Skiku’s mission is to foster the health and recreational benefits of skiing, biathlon and running through sustainable programs across Alaska.

Skiku’s vision is healthy and active families enjoying Alaska’s vast and beautiful landscape on skis.

Skiku and NANANordic programs provide annual Nordic skiing instruction to the children and communities of urban and rural Alaska. Teams of staff and volunteer coaches instruct at local schools, supplementing the physical education classes. After-school Nordic ski sessions are held daily for both children and their families.

post_text: Hunter, Qaiyaan Harcharek, recently shared experiences about hunting, explaining routes and place names with students at Kiita Learning Center in Tennessee Judkins’ class. Ms. Judkins is a student teacher at Kiita Learning Center and is teaching North Slope History as part of her Master’s program at the University of Alaska Southeast. She is currently teaching a unit on North Slope Borough place names which include traditional place names as well as some of the English counterparts in an effort to teach students the histories and uses behind some of these areas on the North Slope.

post_text: Mr. Taylor’s 4th grade class from Ipalook Elementary School in Utqiağġvik, participated in an owl dissection activity on Tuesday, November 28th. The class has been reading a novel Hoot learning about owl habitats and the endangerment of owls losing their habitats to construction projects. The class has also been studying animal adaptations and even adopted a Snowy Owl from the Alaska Raptor Center in Sitka, Alaska. Mr. Taylor’s class would like to thank the Raptor Center for the donations of owl pellets.

Halloween Goodie Sale TODAY!
Students at Kiita Learning Community in Utqiaġvik, are learning how to conduct small businesses, and will be doing a Halloween goodie sale to practice what they have learned. They are selling pumpkin cakes, witch hat cookies, Frankenstein rice crispy treats, pumpkin/bat/skull shaped cookies, spider web brownies and cupcakes. They will be taking pre-orders that can be picked up on Friday, October 27, from 2 p.m to 4 p.m at the Kiita building.

please email MJ Geiser: MaryJane.Geiser@nsbsd.org.

post_text: We ask that everyone take the time to talk to our children about the dangers of thin ice around the lagoon in Utqiaġvik, as well as all bodies of water in the villages across the North Slope. Please remind children about he uncertainty of the thickness of the ice along with the danger in playing near the edge of the ice and what might happen if the ice breaks. Your help in reminding children about these dangers at this time of year is greatly appreciated!

post_text:
NSBSD Needs School Bus Drivers in Utqiaġvik
* Work the same days your children are in school with this fun and rewarding career.
* Paid training to obtain your Alaska Commercial Driver’s License with required Passenger and School Bus endorsements.
* Full-time and substitute school bus driver positions open.
*Starting wage is $24.32/hour.
If you are interested or you need more information, please email the NSBSD Transportation Manager (vicky.churchill@nsbsd.org) or call 852-8987.

post_text: This is Mrs. Harvey's first grade class at Tikiġaq School in Point Hope. They are working on their Netting Numbers cultural unit. The students are estimating and measuring how many fish will fit into the different sized nets.
